    <section class="page">
        <div class="page-number">Page | 5</div>
        <h2>Abstract</h2>
        <p>
            FlashIn Delivery is a web-based last-mile route planning and delivery
            management system. The main purpose of the project is to help a local
            delivery organization manage the movement of customer orders from stores or
            warehouses to final customer addresses. The system provides a centralized
            interface for managing delivery centers, delivery partners, customer orders,
            and delivery routes.
        </p>
        <p>
            The project was developed using Laravel, Blade, Bootstrap, PHP, and SQLite.
            It follows a simple Model-View-Controller structure. The dashboard provides
            operational metrics such as total orders, delivered orders, active drivers,
            route counts, and recent delivery activity. CRUD functionality is provided
            for all major entities so that the user can create, view, update, and delete
            operational records.
        </p>
        <p>
            The application is useful for college-level demonstration of full-stack web
            development, database design, route management, form validation, and
            responsive user interface design. It also demonstrates how delivery
            operations can be digitized to reduce manual work and improve visibility.
        </p>
        <p><strong>Keywords:</strong> Last-mile delivery, route planning, Laravel, CRUD, delivery management, dashboard, logistics.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="page">
        <div class="page-number">Page | 6</div>
        <h2>1. Introduction</h2>
        <h3>1.1 Overview of the Website</h3>
        <p>
            FlashIn Delivery is designed as an administrative web application for
            managing local delivery operations. The website allows the operator to
            maintain records of fulfillment centers, drivers, orders, and routes. It is
            especially suitable for grocery, essentials, and local retail delivery
            businesses where orders must be assigned and tracked quickly.
        </p>
        <h3>1.2 Need and Importance of Last-Mile Delivery</h3>
        <p>
            Last-mile delivery is the final stage in the delivery process, where goods
            are transported from a hub or store to the customer. This stage is important
            because it directly affects customer satisfaction, delivery time, and
            operational cost. Manual tracking can lead to delays, duplicate work, poor
            assignment decisions, and limited visibility. A digital system helps the
            organization keep data organized and improves decision-making.
        </p>
        <h3>1.3 Objectives of the Website</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>To provide a simple dashboard for monitoring delivery operations.</li>
            <li>To manage delivery centers, warehouses, and local stores.</li>
            <li>To create and maintain driver details with availability status.</li>
            <li>To create customer orders and assign them to drivers and routes.</li>
            <li>To create route records with start location, end location, distance, and estimated time.</li>
            <li>To provide a professional and responsive interface for project demonstration.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="page">
        <div class="page-number">Page | 7</div>
        <h2>2. Project Modules and Features</h2>
        <h3>2.1 Dashboard Module</h3>
        <p>
            The dashboard is the first screen of the website. It displays important
            summary values including total orders, delivered orders, active drivers,
            total routes, pending orders, assigned orders, delivery centers, recent
            orders, and recent routes. This gives the user a quick operational view.
        </p>
        <h3>2.2 Main Modules</h3>
        <table>
            <tr><th>Module</th><th>Description</th></tr>
            <tr><td>Delivery Centers</td><td>Stores, warehouses, and grocery hubs can be added and managed with location, contact information, type, status, and coordinates.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Drivers</td><td>Delivery partners can be stored with phone number, vehicle type, license number, assigned center, and working status.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Orders</td><td>Customer orders include order number, customer details, delivery address, items, status, assigned driver, store, and route.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Routes</td><td>Routes store route name, driver, start and end locations, coordinates, estimated distance, estimated time, and current status.</td></tr>
        </table>
        <h3>2.3 Key Features</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Responsive navigation with active page highlighting.</li>
            <li>Professional Bootstrap-based user interface.</li>
            <li>Form validation for required fields and database relationships.</li>
            <li>Pagination for large lists of orders, routes, drivers, and centers.</li>
            <li>Status badges for quick identification of delivery progress.</li>
            <li>SQLite database support for easy local setup.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="page">
        <div class="page-number">Page | 8</div>
        <h2>3. Literature Survey</h2>
        <h3>3.1 Last-Mile Delivery Management</h3>
        <p>
            Last-mile delivery systems focus on organizing orders, delivery partners,
            and dispatch routes. Existing logistics platforms show that centralized
            tracking reduces operational confusion and improves customer service.
            Delivery systems generally require a clear relationship between hubs,
            drivers, orders, and routes.
        </p>
        <h3>3.2 Route Planning and Operational Tracking</h3>
        <p>
            Route planning is important because delivery time and distance affect cost.
            Modern systems often combine route information, driver assignment, and
            order status. FlashIn implements the foundational version of this workflow
            by storing route distance, estimated time, start and end coordinates, and
            route status.
        </p>
        <h3>3.3 Web-Based CRUD Systems</h3>
        <p>
            CRUD applications are widely used in business software because they allow
            users to create, read, update, and delete records. Laravel is useful for
            such systems because it provides routing, controllers, validation, Blade
            templates, database migrations, and Eloquent ORM. These features helped in
            developing FlashIn as a structured and maintainable project.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="page">
        <div class="page-number">Page | 9</div>
        <h2>4. Flow of the Work</h2>
        <h3>4.1 User Journey on the Website</h3>
        <p>
            The user begins from the dashboard, where operational statistics are shown.
            From the navigation bar, the user can open Centers, Drivers, Orders, or
            Routes. The user first creates delivery centers, then adds drivers assigned
            to those centers. After that, customer orders can be created and associated
            with available centers, drivers, and routes.
        </p>
        <div class="diagram">
            <div class="flow">
                <div class="box">Open Dashboard</div>
                <div class="arrow">-&gt;</div>
                <div class="box">Manage Centers and Drivers</div>
                <div class="arrow">-&gt;</div>
                <div class="box">Create Orders</div>
                <div class="box">Create Routes</div>
                <div class="arrow">-&gt;</div>
                <div class="box">Assign Driver and Route</div>
                <div class="arrow">-&gt;</div>
                <div class="box">Track Status</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <h3>4.2 Navigation and Workflow</h3>
        <p>
            The website contains a clear top navigation bar with Dashboard, Centers,
            Drivers, Orders, and Routes. Every module contains listing, creation,
            editing, detail view, and deletion actions. The forms use Laravel
            validation to prevent invalid entries, and success messages are shown after
            important operations.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="page">
        <div class="page-number">Page | 10</div>
        <h2>5. Comparative Analysis of Delivery Applications</h2>
        <h3>5.1 Review of Existing Delivery Platforms</h3>
        <p>
            Popular delivery platforms such as Blinkit, Zepto, Swiggy Instamart, and
            Dunzo provide fast local delivery experiences. They include advanced
            features such as live tracking, automated dispatching, inventory
            management, payment systems, and customer mobile applications. FlashIn is a
            smaller academic system focused on the core administrative workflow.
        </p>
        <h3>5.2 Feature Comparison</h3>
        <table>
            <tr><th>Feature</th><th>Existing Apps</th><th>FlashIn Project</th></tr>
            <tr><td>Order Management</td><td>Advanced customer-facing order lifecycle.</td><td>Admin can create, edit, assign, and update orders.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Driver Management</td><td>Driver apps with live status and GPS.</td><td>Admin can maintain driver records and status.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Route Planning</td><td>Automated routing and live tracking.</td><td>Manual route creation with distance and estimated time.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Dashboard</td><td>Advanced analytics and monitoring.</td><td>Simple operational metrics and recent activity.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Technology Scope</td><td>Large-scale cloud and mobile infrastructure.</td><td>Laravel web application suitable for academic demonstration.</td></tr>
        </table>
        <h3>5.3 Strengths and Limitations</h3>
        <p>
            The major strength of FlashIn is its simplicity. It is easy to understand,
            run, and demonstrate. Its limitation is that it does not yet include
            real-time GPS tracking, automated route optimization, customer login, or
            payment integration. These can be added in future versions.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="page">
        <div class="page-number">Page | 11</div>
        <h2>6. Software and Tools Utilized</h2>
        <h3>6.1 Overview of Software Used</h3>
        <table>
            <tr><th>Software / Tool</th><th>Use in Project</th></tr>
            <tr><td>Laravel</td><td>Backend framework used for routing, controllers, validation, models, migrations, and Blade views.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>PHP</td><td>Server-side programming language for application logic.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Blade</td><td>Laravel templating engine used to build reusable web pages.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Bootstrap</td><td>Responsive layout and UI components.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Font Awesome</td><td>Icons used in navigation, dashboard, and action buttons.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>SQLite</td><td>Local database used for storing project records.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Git and GitHub</td><td>Version control and remote repository hosting.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Composer</td><td>PHP dependency manager.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Vite / NPM</td><td>Frontend asset tooling available in the Laravel setup.</td></tr>
        </table>
        <h3>6.2 Database Design</h3>
        <p>
            The database contains four main project tables: delivery_centers, drivers,
            orders, and routes. These tables are connected through foreign keys, which
            maintain relationships between stores, drivers, route assignments, and
            customer orders.
        </p>
    </section>

