    <section class="page">
        <div class="page-number">Page | 13</div>
        <h2>7. System Analysis and Requirements</h2>
        <h3>7.1 Problem Statement</h3>
        <p>
            Many small delivery businesses still manage daily orders using notebooks,
            spreadsheets, phone calls, and messaging applications. This method becomes
            difficult when order volume increases because store managers need to know
            which driver is available, which order is pending, which route is active,
            and how many orders are already completed. Lack of a centralized system can
            create confusion, repeated communication, delayed delivery, and poor
            tracking of operational records.
        </p>
        <p>
            FlashIn solves this problem by providing a single web interface for the
            main delivery workflow. The operator can create delivery centers, register
            drivers, create orders, plan routes, and monitor statuses from one place.
            The project focuses on the administrative side of last-mile delivery and
            gives a clear base for future real-time tracking and route optimization.
        </p>
        <h3>7.2 Functional Requirements</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>The system should allow the admin to add, update, view, and delete delivery centers.</li>
            <li>The system should store driver details such as name, phone, vehicle type, license number, assigned center, and status.</li>
            <li>The system should allow creation of customer orders with address, items, store, driver, route, and order status.</li>
            <li>The system should allow route creation with start location, end location, coordinates, distance, time, driver, and route status.</li>
            <li>The dashboard should show total orders, delivered orders, active drivers, total routes, centers, recent orders, and recent routes.</li>
            <li>The system should validate input forms and show error messages when required data is missing.</li>
        </ul>
        <h3>7.3 Non-Functional Requirements</h3>
        <table>
            <tr><th>Requirement</th><th>Description</th></tr>
            <tr><td>Usability</td><td>The interface should be simple enough for an operator to use without technical training.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Responsiveness</td><td>The website should work on desktop and smaller screens using responsive Bootstrap layout.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Maintainability</td><td>The code should follow Laravel MVC structure so that modules can be updated independently.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Reliability</td><td>Database relationships and validation should reduce invalid records.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Portability</td><td>The system should run locally using PHP, Composer, SQLite, and Laravel.</td></tr>
        </table>
    </section>

    <section class="page">
        <div class="page-number">Page | 14</div>
        <h2>8. Implementation Details</h2>
        <h3>8.1 Architecture Used</h3>
        <p>
            The project follows the Model-View-Controller architecture provided by
            Laravel. In this pattern, models represent database entities, views present
            information to the user, and controllers handle requests, validation, and
            communication between models and views. This separation makes the project
            easy to understand and improves maintainability.
        </p>
        <table>
            <tr><th>Layer</th><th>Files / Components</th><th>Purpose</th></tr>
            <tr><td>Model</td><td>DeliveryCenter, Driver, Order, Route</td><td>Defines data relationships and database interaction.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>View</td><td>Blade templates inside resources/views</td><td>Displays dashboard, lists, forms, detail pages, and status badges.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Controller</td><td>DashboardController, DeliveryCenterController, DriverWebController, OrderWebController, RouteWebController</td><td>Handles page requests, form validation, CRUD operations, and redirects.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Database</td><td>Laravel migrations and SQLite</td><td>Stores project data in structured tables.</td></tr>
        </table>
        <h3>8.2 Controller Logic</h3>
        <p>
            Each module uses a controller that provides standard resource methods:
            index, create, store, show, edit, update, and destroy. For example, the
            order controller loads active delivery centers, available drivers, and
            route records before displaying the order creation form. When a form is
            submitted, Laravel validation checks the data before creating or updating
            the record in the database.
        </p>
        <h3>8.3 User Interface Implementation</h3>
        <p>
            The interface is built using Blade, Bootstrap, Font Awesome, and a custom
            theme stylesheet. The design uses a professional operations-console look
            with a navy header, white content cards, status badges, responsive tables,
            and clean forms. Common layout elements such as the navigation bar, footer,
            error messages, and success alerts are placed in the shared layout file so
            that all pages maintain the same appearance.
        </p>
        <h3>8.4 Database Relationships</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>A delivery center can have multiple drivers.</li>
            <li>A delivery center can have multiple orders.</li>
            <li>A driver can be assigned to multiple orders and routes.</li>
            <li>An order can optionally belong to a route and driver.</li>
            <li>A route can be assigned to a driver and can be connected to orders.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="page">
        <div class="page-number">Page | 15</div>
        <h2>9. Testing and Validation</h2>
        <h3>9.1 Testing Approach</h3>
        <p>
            Testing was performed by running the Laravel project locally and checking
            each major module. The dashboard, centers page, drivers page, orders page,
            and routes page were opened in the browser to confirm that the pages load
            correctly. Forms were checked by entering valid and invalid data to confirm
            that validation rules work as expected.
        </p>
        <h3>9.2 Test Cases</h3>
        <table>
            <tr><th>Test Case</th><th>Expected Result</th><th>Status</th></tr>
            <tr><td>Open dashboard URL</td><td>Dashboard should load and show delivery metrics.</td><td>Passed</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Create delivery center</td><td>New center should be saved and displayed in the centers list.</td><td>Passed</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Create driver</td><td>Driver should be saved with vehicle and assigned center details.</td><td>Passed</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Create order</td><td>Order number and customer order details should be stored.</td><td>Passed</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Create route</td><td>Route should be saved with driver, locations, distance, time, and status.</td><td>Passed</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Submit empty required fields</td><td>Validation message should be shown and record should not be saved.</td><td>Passed</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Delete a record</td><td>Selected record should be removed after confirmation.</td><td>Passed</td></tr>
        </table>
        <h3>9.3 Validation Rules</h3>
        <p>
            Laravel validation is used to protect the application from incomplete or
            invalid input. Required fields include customer name, phone, delivery
            address, delivery center, route name, route distance, route time, and
            status. Foreign key validation ensures that selected drivers, centers, and
            routes already exist in the database.
        </p>
        <h3>9.4 Result of Testing</h3>
        <p>
            The system successfully supports the expected CRUD workflow. The pages load
            correctly, records are stored in SQLite, and the user receives success or
            validation messages based on the performed action. This confirms that the
            core last-mile delivery management workflow is functional.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="page">
        <div class="page-number">Page | 16</div>
        <h2>10. Advantages, Limitations, and Applications</h2>
        <h3>10.1 Advantages</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Centralizes delivery center, driver, route, and order information.</li>
            <li>Reduces manual record keeping and makes data easier to search and update.</li>
            <li>Provides a quick dashboard summary for operational monitoring.</li>
            <li>Uses a simple and professional interface suitable for academic demonstration.</li>
            <li>Uses Laravel MVC, which makes the project structured and scalable.</li>
            <li>Can be run locally with SQLite, so setup is simple for evaluation.</li>
        </ul>
        <h3>10.2 Limitations</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>The current version does not include login authentication or user roles.</li>
            <li>Route optimization is manual and does not calculate the best path automatically.</li>
            <li>Live GPS tracking is not implemented in this version.</li>
            <li>The system does not include customer mobile application features.</li>
            <li>Payment, invoice, and notification modules are outside the current scope.</li>
        </ul>
        <h3>10.3 Real-World Applications</h3>
        <p>
            FlashIn can be used as a basic administrative system for small courier
            businesses, grocery delivery stores, campus delivery teams, local retail
            logistics, and academic demonstrations. It is also useful as a foundation
            for developing larger logistics applications because its entities match
            real delivery operations: centers, drivers, orders, and routes.
        </p>
        <h3>10.4 Learning Outcomes</h3>
        <p>
            Through this project, important concepts of web development were practiced,
            including MVC architecture, database migrations, CRUD operations, form
            validation, responsive layout design, route definitions, template reuse,
            version control, and project deployment preparation.
        </p>
    </section>

